# CONTENT MIGRATION STRATEGY

## Purpose

Define how legacy content is discovered, validated, and prepared for migration so launch achieves parity-first SEO continuity.
This strategy is pre-actionable by design; detailed execution planning happens after scrape completion.

## Strategic Objectives

- Preserve organic performance by mirroring legacy URLs, content intent, and internal linking.
- Build a complete and auditable inventory before implementation decisions.
- Migrate NL and EN content with consistent language routing (`/` and `/en/`).
- Keep migration deterministic via manifests, coverage reports, and validation gates.

## Source-of-Truth Hierarchy

1. XML sitemaps for indexable URL scope.
2. WordPress exports for structured legacy fields.
3. Firecrawl for rendered page content, DOM structure, and internal link graph.
4. Existing media references from sitemap, page content, and exports.
5. Strapi for escort profile entities and availability (target runtime source).

## Migration Scope Policy

- Phase 1 policy: mirror-first with minor editorial fixes only.
- No changes that alter search intent, canonical URL intent, or core page semantics.
- For every migrated URL+locale in Phase 1, the launch `meta title` and `meta description` must exactly match the live legacy page text.
- Metadata deviations are allowed only with explicit SEO signoff and a documented exception (reason, owner, date, affected URL+locale).
- Any unavoidable URL delta requires explicit redirect mapping and approval.
- Out-of-scope changes are logged into post-launch optimization backlog.

## Required Discovery Outputs (Before Action Plan)

- Canonical URL inventory (NL + EN), deduped and typed.
- Page parity inventory: legacy URL -> planned Next.js route.
- Content block map per page template (headings, body sections, CTA blocks).
- Internal link graph export (source URL -> destination URL).
- Media inventory with reusable asset mapping.
- Blog inventory with taxonomy and publish metadata where available.
- Strapi coverage check for profile fields and availability dependencies.

## Validation Gates (Must Pass Before Build)

- Coverage gate: all in-scope URLs are classified (`include`, `review`, `exclude`).
- Content gate: critical commercial pages have full content parity records.
- Link gate: key internal pathways are preserved.
- Metadata gate: title/meta/canonical/hreflang requirements mapped, with exact-match validation for `meta title` and `meta description` against legacy per URL+locale.
- Media gate: missing/broken assets are below agreed threshold.
- Language gate: NL/EN alternates and route strategy are defined for all in-scope pages.

## Decision Rules During Migration

- If source mismatch exists, prefer sitemap + rendered page reality over assumptions.
- If WP export data is incomplete, proceed with scrape baseline and flag enrichment backlog.
- If content duplicates exist across locales, preserve locale-specific canonical intent.
- If a page cannot be mirrored exactly, escalate and decide between:
  - parity workaround in Next.js, or
  - controlled URL/content deviation with redirect + SEO signoff.

## Risks and Mitigations

- Hidden legacy URLs not in sitemap:
  - Mitigation: union sitemap + crawl-discovered URLs, then classify.
- Internal link loss during component rebuild:
  - Mitigation: enforce link parity checks before release.
- Metadata drift from template changes:
  - Mitigation: page-level metadata mapping and pre-launch QA crawl.
- Media gaps or mismatched references:
  - Mitigation: hash-based media inventory and broken-asset reports.

## Post-Scrape Handoff (Actionable Planning Trigger)

After scraping and inventories are complete, produce a separate actionable plan that converts strategy to execution tickets.

Create:
- `.cursor/plans/CONTENT_MIGRATION_ACTION_PLAN.md`

This actionable plan must include:
- Route-by-route migration batches (priority order).
- Component/template mapping by page type.
- Exact field mapping (WordPress/Firecrawl -> Next.js/Strapi).
- Redirect matrix (only where required).
- QA checklist per batch (content, links, metadata, hreflang, media).
- Owners, effort estimate, dependencies, and acceptance criteria per batch.

## Definition of Ready for Action Plan

- Scrape run complete with failure report and retries documented.
- URL inventory finalized and approved.
- Page and media parity maps available.
- Strapi model fit reviewed and known gaps logged.
- SEO parity constraints accepted by project stakeholders.

## Definition of Done for Migration Phase 1

- All approved in-scope pages are live with parity intent preserved.
- Critical metadata and internal links match migration requirements.
- `Meta title` and `meta description` are exact text matches to legacy for all approved URL+locale pairs, except approved and documented exceptions.
- NL/EN routing parity is correct.
- Redirects and 404 monitoring are in place.
- Post-launch optimization backlog is documented and prioritized.
